Introduction¶

In part A, we had analysed the loan data with the aim to understand and summarise the different behaviours or attributes between customers who paid back their loan and customers who did not. This time around, we take a more advanced approach, we use the historical data to design a process which predicts the likelihood of a new customer not paying back their loan. In other to achieve this set objective, we shall be using some machine learning approaches available in literature. This part of the work is primarily aimed at building a predictive model.

In the end, we shall compare the different machine learning algorithms used using different accuuracy metrics and choose the one which performs best as our choice model.

We proceeded with the task here by using the already clean data from part A.

The enumerated steps below highlights how we achieved our objective for this project.

Data => cleaned loan dataset from part A

  1. Wranging Steps
  • drop:
    • emp_title, addr_state
  • one-hot encode [func] :
    • home_ownership, term
  • encode [func] :
    • purpose, loan_status, emp_length
  1. standard & robust scaling
  2. remove highly correlated variables.
  3. train/test split [80/20], stratify,
  4. Models under review:
  • Isolation Forest
  • One Class SVM
  • Local Outlier Factor
  • KNN
  • Logistic Regression
  1. hyperparameter tuning:
  • gridsearch cv
  1. accuracy metrics
  • roc/auc curves, f1, recall
  • classification report
  • train/test accuracy
  • feature importance per model [plot into bar chart]
  • confusion matrix [for models]

Data Preprocessing¶

We take 'Charged Off' as our positive class since we are interested in a customer not paying back.

We make a correlation plot and possibly remove highly correlating ($r \geq \pm9$ ) columns. Where $r$ is the correlation coefficient.

From the above correlation heatmap, we drop term_36 months and loan_amnt because of their high correlation to term_60 months and installment respectively.

Standard Scaling, Robust Scaling & Train-Test Split¶

The box plot below shows that our dataset is still filled with an overwhelming amount of outliers and standard scaling did not help in this regard. Now, we use Robust Scaling for these columns.

Models¶

A. Isolation Forest¶

array([[  521,  1761],
       [ 2826, 10755]])

We have that to be the confusion matrix of the isolation forest model, we understand it better with the classification report.

              precision    recall  f1-score   support

          -1       0.16      0.23      0.19      2282
           1       0.86      0.79      0.82     13581

    accuracy                           0.71     15863

We can see that the precision for '-1' our Charged off class is really low. As a result, this model is not ideal.

The curve also shows the model's inability to differentiate the classes.

Accuracy in Detecting Fully Paid Cases: 0.8514376996805112
Accuracy in Detecting Charged Off Cases: 0.155661786674634

With the accuracy shown, we are dissatified with this model.

Text(0, 0.5, 'Variables')

From the above, interest rate, loan tenor of 60 months, and installment are key to predicting a customer defaulter. Also, on the negative scale, the average current balance is a key feature as well.

Prediction Probabilities: KNN vs LR¶

In conclusion, the logistic regression is our best model amongst the three presented.
